05026nam a22006375i 9780292756069DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20211994txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927560697 a10.7560/7079932doi  a(DE-B1597)588480  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aQH75b.B43 1994 7aNAT0000002bisacsh04a333.95/4162201 aBeatley, Timothy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHabitat Conservation Planning :bEndangered Species and Urban Growth /cTimothy Beatley. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1994  a1 online resource (246 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tCHAPTER ONE Land Development and Endangered Species: Emerging Conflicts -- tCHAPTER TWO The Federal Endangered Species Act: Key Provisions and Implications for Land Development -- tCHAPTER THREE Overview of Past and Ongoing Habitat Conservation Plans and Processes -- tCHAPTER FOUR The Politics of Habitat Conservation Planning: Key Actors and Perspectives -- tCHAPTER FIVE Habitat Conservation Plans to Protect Butterflies and Other Invertebrate Species: San Bruno Mountain and Beyond -- tCHAPTER SIX Conserving Habitat for a Threatened Desert Lizard: The Coachella Valley Habitat Conservation Plan -- tCHAPTER SEVEN Habitat Conservation in the Florida Keys: The North Key Largo Habitat Conservation Plan -- tCHAPTER EIGHT Protecting Migratory Songbirds: The Least Bell's Vireo Habitat Conservation Plan -- tCHAPTER NINE Endangered Rats and Endangered Homeowners: The Affordable Housing/Species Clash in Riverside County -- tCHAPTER TEN Preserving the Desert Tortoise: The Clark County Habitat Conservation Plan -- tCHAPTER ELEVEN Preserving the Kit Fox and Other Flora and Fauna of the San Joaquin Valley: The Bakersfield and Kern County Habitat Conservation Plans -- tCHAPTER TWELVE The Promise of Regional, Multi-species Approaches: The Balcones Canyonlands Conservation Plan -- tCHAPTER THIRTEEN Evaluating the Success of Habitat Conservation Efforts: Lessons Learned and Recommendations for the Future -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs environmental awareness grows around the world, people are learning that a diversity of species and the habitat to support them is necessary to maintain the ecological health of the earth. At the same time, however, the pressure to develop wildlife habitat for human settlement and economic gain also grows, causing frequent clashes between the forces of development and of conservation. This pioneering study focuses on a new tool for resolving the land-use conflict—the creation of habitat conservation plans (HCPs). Timothy Beatley explores the development and early results of this provision of the United States' federal Endangered Species Act, which allows development of some habitat and a certain "take" of a protected species in return for the conservation of sufficient habitat to ensure its survival and long-term recovery. Beatley looks specifically at nine HCPs in California, Nevada, Texas, and Florida, states where biological diversity and increasing populations have triggered many conflicts. Some of the HCPs include the San Bruno Mountain HCP near San Francisco, the North Key Largo HCP in the Florida Keys, the Clark County HCP near Las Vegas, Nevada, and the Balcones Canyonlands HCP near Austin, Texas. This first comprehensive overview of habitat conservation planning in the United States will be important reading for everyone involved in land-use debates.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aBiodiversity conservation. 0aCity planningxEnvironmental aspects. 0aEndangered species. 0aHabitat conservationxPlanning. 0aHabitat c